Juana Confesora is a hard-working woman and a proud mother of four children ranging in age from 14 to 17, all of whom attend school.  For more than 10 years, she’s been able to sustain her family by selling an assortment of tablecloths, decorative window curtains and clothing in Sabana Grande de Boya, a community located in the province of Monte Plata with a population of about 15500 inhabitants.  Juana still operates her business in the streets.  She says that she can’t afford to rent an establishment because of the high costs.  She prefers to visit friends, neighbors, and go to the public places to offer her goods.  From January on, the entrepreneur plans to test new waters by adding silver-plated jewelry to the business.  She hopes that she’ll have success in her endeavor.  With this loan, Juana will buy more tablecloths and curtains to sell during the Christmas period.  The entrepreneur wants to increase her revenue to keep supporting her children’s education.

Juana will receive her loan together with these women:
Rosa C. R., a clothing retailer;
Odalis A. S., who sells footwear;
M. M. G., who sells empanadas;
Maria M. S., who operates a fruit stand;
In the picture, Juana Confesora is first on the left.
